[h1]The background-clip Property[/h1]

The [b]background-clip[/b] property specifies the painting area of the background.

[b][/b]The property takes three different values:

[b]border-box[/b] - (default) the background is painted to the outside edge of the border
[b]padding-box[/b] - the background is painted to the outside edge of the padding
[b]content-box[/b] - the background is painted within the content box

In the example below, the first div with background-clip is set to [b]padding-box;[/b] in the second div it's set to [b]content-box[/b].[code format="css" codeId="611"]#first {
   border: 2px dotted black;
   padding: 20px;
   background: LightBlue;
   [b]background-clip: padding-box[/b];
}
#second {
   border: 2px dotted black;
   padding: 20px;
   background: LightBlue;
   [b]background-clip: content-box;[/b]
}[/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2699" width="100%"]

[h1]background-clip with Images[/h1]

background-clip also applies to background images.
[b]The CSS:[/b][code format="css" codeId="612"]div {
   background-image: url("css-logo.png");
   background-clip: content-box;
}[/code]
[img id="2700" width="100%"]
